@NODE MAIN "AnsiRead, v1.01 (28-Sep-96) by Dotoran of Frontiers!"
@FONT Times.font 24
@{JCENTER}@{H1 "  Presenting...  "}

@{"        AnsiRead, v1.01        " link CONTENTS}

@{H1 " by Dotoran of Frontiers! "}
@ENDNODE
@NODE CONTENTS "AnsiRead's Table of Contents"
                          @{U}The Table of Contents@{CL}

@{"What Is AnsiRead(er)?" link WHAT}  - Explains why you should use AnsiRead!

@{"Installing AnsiRead?!" link INSTALL}  - One easy step to install this file! :-)

@{"How to Use AnsiRead?!" link HOW} - Here's the MEATY portion. How to effectively USE
                        the AnsiRead(er) in your own doors/scripts!

@{"AnsiRead's Commands?!" link COMMANDS} - Explanations of AnsiRead's commands.

@{"Why Was It Written?!?" link WHY} - Well, click the button and find out! !sheesh! :-)

@{"Some AnsiRead Ideas!?" link IDEAS} - Some ideas on using AnsiRead on your bbs!
@ENDNODE
@NODE WHAT "What IS AnsiRead(er) Anyways?!?"
@TOC CONTENTS
   AnsiRead was written out of neccessity, as I wanted to include a way
for the users and SysOps to be able to read text files, both with and
without embedded MCI/ANSI codes in a timely fashion.

   I also wanted the ability to page through the document quickly and
easily, as well as being able to search out specific text strings. The
farther I went with the idea, the more powerful the program became! :-)

   I also wanted the file to be EXTERNAL, so that I could CALL it from
any file I wanted to, so the users could get used to seeing it, and take
advantage of it's power whenever possible.

   Another consideration had to be the color-scheme used, because I
wanted it to blend in with whatever program I used it with, so I gave it
the ability to use specific colors, if given, or to use internal defaults
if not given.

   Lastly, some of the programs I'm working on needed the ability to use
an ansi-read type program, but in such a way, so as to fit on the screen
at the same time as other things, so it's possible to specify how LARGE
or SMALL you wish the AnsiRead program to be, so you can display other info
on the screen at the same time as viewing whatever documents you wish!
@ENDNODE
@NODE INSTALL "How to INSTALL AnsiRead, v1.01!"
@TOC CONTENTS
   Watch how easy this one is:

1> Copy the "AnsiRead", "AnsiRead.Help", and the "AnsiRead.guide" files
   into any directory of your own choosing, so long as all three are
   located in the SAME directory.

2> That's it!

                                                Yep!     YOU'RE DONE!!!

:-)
@ENDNODE
@NODE HOW "Here's HOW to USE the AnsiRead program!"
@TOC CONTENTS
   If you load the "AnsiRead" program into a text editor and look at the
numerous initial lines of coding, you'll see the following:

if @{"c1" link C1}="" then c1="7"  /* 7  Color for title bar BG color.      (0-7)      */
if @{"c2" link C2}="" then c2="1"  /* 1  Color for title bar FG color.      (0-9/a-f)  */
if @{"c3" link C3}="" then c3="2"  /* 2  Color for twirly-gig/marked lines. (0-9/a-f)  */
if @{"c4" link C4}="" then c4="9"  /* 9  Color for found text strings.      (0-9/a-f)  */
if @{"c5" link C5}="" then c5="5"  /* 5  Color for BG of info line.         (0-7)      */
if @{"c6" link C6}="" then c6="e"  /* e  Color for FG of info line.         (0-9/a-f)  */
if @{"cn" link CN}="" then cn=0    /* 0  Load as CNet Formatted text file?  (0=N,1=Y)  */
if @{"sm" link SM}="" then sm=1    /* 1  Strip Mci-Codes from texts?        (0=N,1=Y)  */
if @{"vh" link VH}="" then vh=20   /* 20 Vertical Height in Lines? (Between 2 and 20)  */
if @{"tb" link TB}="" then tb=1    /* 1  Title Bar Start Row?   (Between 1 and 22-VH)  */
if @{"hf" link HF}="" then hf=0    /* 0  Show Help First Thing?             (0=N,1=Y)  */
if @{"up" link UP}="" then up=0    /* 0  Use UUCP Path for MarkSaves?       (0=N,1=Y)  */

Click a button above for a detailed description of that variable setting...

...or click @{"Using AnsiRead from within other files" link USING}
@ENDNODE
@NODE C1 "Background Color of the Title Bar"
@TOC HOW
if c1="" then c1="7"  /* 7  Color for title bar BG color.      (0-7)      */

   AnsiRead uses three rows of the screen to display information about the
current file being viewed, possible commands, etc. Two of these lines are
above the text displayed, while the third lies below the text.

   This variable allows you to specify the color to be used for the back-
ground of these three lines. You can specify any MCI Color code from 0 to
7 for this variable.
@ENDNODE
@NODE C2 "Foreground Color of the Title Bar"
@TOC HOW
if c2="" then c2="1"  /* 1  Color for title bar FG color.      (0-9/a-f)  */

   AnsiRead uses three rows of the screen to display information about the
current file being viewed, possible commands, etc. Two of these lines are
above the text displayed, while the third lies below the text.

   This variable allows you to specify the color to be used for the fore-
ground of these three lines. In other words, the color of the text itself.
You can choose to use any valid MCI Color code between 0 and 9, or between
A and F.
@ENDNODE
@NODE C3 "The Color of the Twirly-Gig & Marked Text"
@TOC HOW
if c3="" then c3="2"  /* 2  Color for twirly-gig/marked lines. (0-9/a-f) */

   Whenever AnsiRead needs to think about something(for instance, when it's
trying to find selected text during a SEARCH operation), it will display a
little spinning character I've come to call the "Twirly-Gig". This variable
lets you choose the color the Twirly-Gig will appear in.

   This value will also be used to define the color AnsiRead will use to
show you MARKED text lines. These `marked text' lines appear only on the
first line of the AnsiRead screen.
@ENDNODE
@NODE C4 "The Color `found text strings' will appear in"
@TOC HOW
if c4="" then c4="9"  /* 9  Color for found text strings.      (0-9/a-f)  */

   When using the SEARCH command of AnsiRead, the program will use this
color to highlight found instances of your text, so as to make it easier
for you to see where the instances occurred.
@ENDNODE
@NODE C5 "The Background Color of the `Headings' bar, if present."
@TOC HOW
if c5="" then c5="5"  /* 5  Color for BG of info line.         (0-7)      */

   AnsiRead excels at displaying text files in a LIST format. Sometimes,
when viewing a list of information, it's helpful to provide headings at
the top of the listing. AnsiRead allows you to create this "Headings" line,
which will be displayed right below the two title bars, but right above the
first line of text. This line will ALWAYS be visible, and will not scroll
off the screen when you traverse through the listing.

   This variable allows you to specify the background color that this bar
will appear in. Values between 0 and 7 can be used here.
@ENDNODE
@NODE C6 "The Foreground Color of the `Headings' bar, if present."
@TOC HOW
if c6="" then c6="e"  /* e  Color for FG of info line.         (0-9/a-f)  */

   AnsiRead excels at displaying text files in a LIST format. Sometimes,
when viewing a list of information, it's helpful to provide headings at
the top of the listing. AnsiRead allows you to create this "Headings" line,
which will be displayed right below the two title bars, but right above the
first line of text. This line will ALWAYS be visible, and will not scroll
off the screen when you traverse through the listing.

   This variable allows you to specify the foreground color, or text color
of the headings. Values between 0 and 9, or A thru F can be used here.
@ENDNODE
@NODE CN "Is the text file a `CNet Formatted' text file?"
@TOC HOW
if cn="" then cn=0    /* 0  Load as CNet Formatted text file?  (0=N,1=Y)  */

   CNet creates text file listings containing a specific number of MCI
Color codes. AnsiRead can take this into consideration when formatting how
the text file will be presented to you in it's window, so that the lines do
not appear to word wrap at the wrong positions.

   If your text files use a list-format with 4 MCI-Color Codes per line,
then enable this variable with a "1", otherwise use the "0" value.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SM "Should embedded Control-Y MCI's be removed from the text?"
@TOC HOW
if sm="" then sm=1    /* 1  Strip Mci-Codes from texts?        (0=N,1=Y)  */

   AnsiRead has the added ability of STRIPPING all 3-character Control-Y
type MCI codes from a text file BEFORE presenting the file to you for your
perusal.

   Instances of Control-Q codes will be converted to open braces ( { ), and
the entire code will be left intact within the document, so you can see what
these codes would do if interpreted.

   It is HIGHLY recommended that you enable this variable(with a "1") if
you'll be using AnsiRead to interpret text files that could contain lethal
MCI commands.

WARNING:

   AnsiRead WILL INTERPRET ALL MCI CODES found within a document. It was
specifically written TO DO THIS, so be absolutely sure the documents you'll
be reading with this program contain "safe" commands and text.
@ENDNODE
@NODE VH "The Vertical Height AnsiRead should use"
@TOC HOW
if vh="" then vh=20   /* 20 Vertical Height in Lines? (Between 2 and 20)  */

   Sometimes, you might find it useful to use the power of AnsiRead on the
screen at the same time as displaying OTHER text somewhere ELSE on the
screen. This variable lets you specify how TALL the AnsiRead screen should
become.

   The value chosen for this variable defines the number of TEXT rows to
use when displaying the text file. It does NOT include the two title bars,
the headings bar, or the bottom border. If a heading bar is included, the
number in this variable will be decreased by one.

   At the smallest setting, AnsiRead will only use 5 lines of your screen!
Used in conjunction with the @{"TB variable" link TB}, you can effectively place the
AnsiRead window anywhere on your screen!
@ENDNODE
@NODE TB "The Row that AnsiRead should START On"
@TOC HOW
if tb="" then tb=1    /* 1  Title Bar Start Row?   (Between 1 and 22-VH)  */

   Used in conjunction with the @{"VH variable" link VH}, this variable allows you to
specify WHERE on the screen you wish the AnsiRead screen to be displayed.

   Using a setting of 5 for TB, with a setting of 15 for this variable will
produce a 5 line text window at the BOTTOM of your screen. This leaves the
initial 14 lines of your screen OPEN to display other things at the same
time you're using the AnsiRead program.
@ENDNODE
@NODE HF "Should the AnsiRead Help Screen Appear First?"
@TOC HOW
if hf="" then hf=0    /* 0  Show Help First Thing?             (0=N,1=Y)  */

   AnsiRead has a separate text file containing a listing of all possible
commands.  The file can be displayed by the user whenever they press the
@{"? or /" link HELP} keys on their keyboard.

   If you'd like the help screen to be displayed BEFORE the user sees your
text file, then enable this variable with a "1". Otherwise, leave it set to
"0".
@ENDNODE
@NODE UP "Should Marked Text be saved to User's Mail Directories?"
@TOC HOW
if up="" then up=0    /* 0  Use UUCP Path for MarkSaves?       (0=N,1=Y)  */

   One of the commands AnsiRead offers is the ability to @{"MARK" link MARKON} portions of
the text file for COPY/WRITING to an external text file.

   When disabled(with a "0"), all marked text saves will be saved to the
same location the initial file was found in.

   If, however, you enable this variable with a "1", the marked portions
can be saved directly to the user's mail directories. This allows the user
the ability of using the .GET command in a CNet Editor to pull the text
into the editor for use in mailings, etc.
@ENDNODE
@NODE USING "How to USE AnsiRead in your OWN programs..."
@TOC HOW
   Use the MCI #0 command to launch instances of AnsiRead in your own files
using the following format:

{#0 <path>:AnsiRead path/filename,c1,c2,c3,c4,c5,c6,cn,sm,vh,tb,hf,up}
~|~ ~~~~~~|~~~~~~~~ ~~~~|~~~~~~~~ ~| ~~ ~~ ~~ ~~ ~~ ~~ ~~ ~~ ~~ ~~ |~|
 |        |             |          `-------------------------------' |
 |        |             |               @{" Variable Settings " link HOW}         |
 |        |             |                                            |
 |        |             `---> The path & filename you wish to load   |
 |        |                   into AnsiRead. (Make Sure It Exists!)  |
 |        |                                                          |
 |        `---> The path where AnsiRead can be located.              |
 |                                                                   |
 `---> These characters are needed by CNet to launch the AnsiRead    |
       file through the MCI interface. Replace { with a Control-Q    |
       character. Use a standard close brace( } ) at the end.    <---'

   If you wish to create a "Headings" bar, you'll need to include a
SETCLIP() command right BEFORE the above command, using this format:

        CALL SETCLIP("ARt","<Your Heading Text>")
        ~~~~|~~~~~~~~ ~|~   ~~~~~~~~~|~~~~~~~~~ |
            |          |   Inside Double Quotes |
            |          |                        |
            |          `--> "AnsiRead Title" &  |
            |               must also be put in |
            |               double quote marks. |
            |                                   |
            |                                   |
            `--> The ARexx SetClip() Command <--'

   Here's an example:

call setclip("ARt","Command      What it will do for you?")
transmit "{#0 doors:ansiread systext:menu/main,4,e,b,9,5,e,1,0}"
call setclip("ARt")

The above 3 commands would load CNet's Main Menu into AnsiRead, using an
appropriate heading bar, with the following values:

Title bars would be dark blue, with bright cyan text. A bright yellow
Twirly-Gig would be used, with found text strings appearing in bright red.
The heading would appear in light cyan on a dark purple background. The
file is a CNet formatted text file, so would appear word-wrap corrected,
and the embedded MCI-Codes would be left intact.

   The second use of the SETCLIP() variable AFTER the use of AnsiRead will
insure the header bar is removed from memory, else it would appear as the
header bar for the next file loaded into AnsiRead, even if it were a file
different from the first. If no header bar is used, then no instances of
the SETCLIP() command are needed.

   It is NOT necessary to include ALL variable settings, however if you'll
be ommitting a value, you must include the comma, which acts as a place
holder for given values, as shown in this example:

transmit "{#0doors:AnsiRead cnet:bbsmenu,,,,,,,,1,10,5,1,1}"

   In this example, the default colors will be used, as will the default
setting for the CNet formatted text value, however all MCI-Codes will be
stripped, and the AnsiRead screen will only appear 10 rows tall, starting
on row 5. The AnsiRead Help Screen will be displayed first, and any marked
saves will be stored in the user's mail directory. Since a header bar was
not included, none will appear.

   When the AnsiRead program is launched, an initial line will be shown,
so that the user has an idea as to how much of the text file has been
loaded into memory. If the user should press a key WHILE the file was being
loaded, the reading will stop at that line and whatever portion was read in
up to that point will be loaded into AnsiRead.

   You can use ANSI positioning codes in FRONT of the {#0 } command to
position this initial line wherever you wish. You can also include MCI
Color codes in front of the {#0 } command to change the color used for
this "read-in" line. The choice is yours!
@ENDNODE
@NODE COMMANDS "Descriptions of the COMMANDS Available in AnsiRead"
@TOC CONTENTS
Click a command to learn more about it...

@{"       7, H " link HOME}: Move to HOME Position (First Line)
@{"       1, E " link END}: Move to END  Position (Last  Line)
@{" <LA>, 9, > " link PAGEUP}: Move UP   ONE PAGE (See Past Screen)
@{" <RA>, 3, < " link PAGEDOWN}: Move DOWN ONE PAGE (See Next Screen)
@{" <UA>, 8, U " link LINEUP}: Move UP   ONE LINE (Text Moves Down)
@{" <DA>, 2, D " link LINEDOWN}: Move DOWN ONE LINE (Text Moves Up)
@{"       L, G " link GOTOLINE}: Move or Goto Specific Line Number within text.
@{"       P, % " link PERCENT}: Move to a Specific Percentage within the text.
@{"       5, S " link SEARCH}: Search for text string (From Current Position)
@{"       4, B " link BSEARCH}: Search BACKWARDS for text string, if it exists.
@{"       6, F " link FSEARCH}: Search FOREWARDS for text string, if it exists.
@{"       M, [ " link MARKON}: Turn MARKING MODE ON.  (Top Line will highlight)
@{"       M, ] " link MARKOFF}: Turn MARKING MODE OFF. (Top Line back to normal)
@{"       V, * " link MARKVIEW}: View Marked Text Block, if one is set currently.
@{"       W, T " link MARKSAVE}: Write(or Take) MARKED text to an external filename.
@{"       J, 0 " link JUMP}: Jump / Skip a Number of Lines Down Into Document.
@{"    <SPACE> " link JUMPSET}: Set JUMP LINES Value. (Skip More Than 1 Line)
@{"       C, K " link COUNT}: Count/Highlight instances of text strings found.
@{"          I " link IMPORT}: Imports an external text file, replacing initial file.
@{"          Z " link TOGGLE}: Toggles Embedded MCI Codes On/Off within text file.
@{"          R " link REDRAW}: ReDraws the screen, in case embedded MCI's go awry.
@{"   <ESC>, Q " link QUIT}: Quit AnsiRead, "ver" (Returns to Calling Program)
@{"       ?, / " link HELP}: Info or Help on using AnsiRead.

After a text file is loaded into AnsiRead, the screen shown will have two
title bars above the text, and one below it, listing the following data:

AnsiRead: Use Arrows to Move, Press ? or / for Help, or Q to Quit  HH:MM?M
 Command:                                        mm1-mm2 (nn1/nn2/nn3/nn4) +


Filename: path:path/filename

In the upper right corner, the current time will be displayed in 12 hour
format. This time is updated every second or so, so can be used from a
remote location to keep track of the time.

The second line will display the currently issued command, followed by
numerous numeric values:

  mm1-mm2   : If present, these values tell you the START and END position
              of the currently MARKED text. Use the "M" command to @{"MARK" link MARKON}
              text inside a document.

      nn1   : This is the line number of the line appearing at the top
              of the text display area.

      nn2   : This is the line number of the line appearing at the bottom
              of the text display area.

      nn3   : This is the total number of lines that have been read into
              the AnsiRead program.

      nn4   : This is the percentage INTO the document the line appearing
              at the bottom of the display is located.

        +   : When shown, the + means the entire document was read into
              AnsiRead, but if a - is shown, reading was stopped early by
              the user.

At the bottom of the screen, you'll be shown the full path and filename of
the current text document. It is also this line where all requests for info
by the user will be displayed by AnsiRead, so keep your eye on this row.

On the right side of this lower bar will also appear "Twirly-Text" whenever
AnsiRead is working and needs you to wait. The "Twirly-Gig" should continue
to spin to let you know it's still working. If it should STOP spinning for
longer than 5 seconds, then you can safely assume something has gone wrong,
and you may have a lockup on your hands.
@ENDNODE
@NODE HOME "Move to Home Position"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The HOME command, issued by the "H" or "7" keys on the keyboard, will
automatically move you to the beginning of the text document.
@ENDNODE
@NODE END "Move to End Position"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The END command, issued by the "E" or "1" keys on the keyboard, will
automatically move you to the end of the text document.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PAGEUP "Move UP one page of text"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The PAGEUP command, issued by the LEFT CURSOR ARROW, "9", ">", or "."
keys on the keyboard, will automatically move the text file UP one screen-
full of text, depending on the size of the AnsiRead window.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PAGEDOWN "Move DOWN one page of text"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The PAGEDOWN command, issued by the RIGHT CURSOR ARROW, "3", "<", or ","
keys on the keyboard, will automatically move the text file DOWN one screen-
full of text, depending on the size of the AnsiRead window.
@ENDNODE
@NODE LINEUP "Move UP one line of text"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The LINEUP command, issued by the UP CURSOR ARROW, "8", or "U" keys on
the keyboard, will move the text UP one row on the screen. The text will
look like it moves down one line.
@ENDNODE
@NODE LINEDOWN "Move DOWN one line of text"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The LINEDOWN command, issued by the DOWN CURSOR ARROW, "2", or "D" keys
on the keyboard, will move the text DOWN one row on the screen. The text
will look like it moves up one line.
@ENDNODE
@NODE GOTOLINE "Goto a SPECIFIC line number within the document"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The GOTOLINE command, issued by the "L" or "G" commands on the keyboard
will allow you to jump to a specific line number within the text document.
The specified line number will appear as the first line of text in the
AnsiRead window.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PERCENT "Goto a SPECIFIC percentage into the document"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The GOTOPERCENT command, issued by the "P" or "%" keys on the keyboard,
will allow you to jump to a specific percentage within the text document.
The first line in the AnsiRead text window will be the percentage position
chosen.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SEARCH "Search for specific text strings"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The SEARCH command, issued by the "5" or "S" keys on the keyboard, will
allow you to enter a text string to search for. The search will begin at
the line shown at the top of the AnsiRead text window.

   Found instances of the search text will be highlighted for clarity.

   Use the @{"FORWARD" link FSEARCH} and/or @{"BACKWARD" link BSEARCH} search commands to further enhance your
searches.

   If the found instances are NOT highlighted, try toggling the MCI setting,
using the "Z" key.
@ENDNODE
@NODE BSEARCH "Search Backwards for specified text string"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The BACKWARDS SEARCH command, issued by the "4" or "B" keys on the key-
board, will start at the text line shown at the top of the AnsiRead text
window and search BACKWARDS for the last entered text string.

   You must have first entered a text string, using the "S" command, before
using this command.

   Found instances of the search text will be highlighted for clarity.

   Use the @{"FORWARD" link FSEARCH} command to further the search capacity, or use @{"SEARCH" link SEARCH}
to specify a different search string.

   If the found instances are NOT highlighted, try toggling the MCI setting,
using the "Z" key.
@ENDNODE
@NODE FSEARCH "Search Forwards for specified text string"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The FORWARDS SEARCH command, issued by the "6" or "F" keys on the key-
board, will start at the text line shown at the top of the AnsiRead text
window and search FORWARDS for the last entered text string.

   You must have first entered a text string, using the "S" command, before
using this command.

   Found instances of the search text will be highlighted for clarity.

   Use the @{"BACKWARD" link BSEARCH} command to further the search capacity, or use @{"SEARCH" link SEARCH}
to specify a different search string.

   If the found instances are NOT highlighted, try toggling the MCI setting,
using the "Z" key.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MARKON "Turn Line Marking ON"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The MARK ON command, issued by the "[" or "M" keys on the keyboard, can
be used to place a MARK in the text which can be used to select portions of
a text document for saving, printing, or exporting to an external file.

   To mark a line of text, you'll need to position the text, so that the
line you'd like to mark is at the TOP of the AnsiRead Text Window.

   When MARKING is enabled, the top text line in the AnsiRead window will
become highlighted, and you'll see it's line number appear in front of a -
in the second title bar at the top of the screen.

   While sitting on the same line number, press "M" or "[" again to cancel
the MARK, or use the movement commands to locate the last line you'd like
to MARK, position that line at the TOP of the AnsiRead Text Window, and hit
the @{" M or ] " link MARKOFF} keys on the keyboard.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MARKOFF "Turn Line Marking OFF"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The MARK OFF command, issued by the "M" or "]" keys on the keyboard, can
only be used if Line Marking was first enabled using the @{" M or [ " link MARKON} keys on
the keyboard.

   You must position the last line you wish to mark at the TOP of the
screen before hitting the M or ] keys to complete the mark.

   When you turn marking OFF, the highlighted line will turn off, and the
line number of that line will appear in the 2nd row of the title bar after
the - symbol to complete the marked range.

   You can then choose to use the @{"VIEW" link MARKVIEW} or @{"WRITE" link MARKSAVE} commands to work with this
marked text range.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MARKVIEW "View previously Marked Lines"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The VIEW MARKED command, issued by the "V" or "*" keys on the keyboard,
will allow you to view a previously marked portion of text.

   If a portion of text has not been marked, then this command will not
function. Check the 2nd row of the title bars to make sure a marked range
has been set(Two numbers, separated with a - mark).
@ENDNODE
@NODE MARKSAVE "Save previously Marked Lines"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The SAVE MARKED command, issued by the "W" or "T" keys on the keyboard,
will allow you to specify a path and filename to save to.

   Depending on the value of the @{"UP variable" link UP}, or the @{"13th argument" link USING} given in
the {#0 } command, a different default path can be used. If set to "0", the
user will see the same path as that which the original file is located,
however if set as "1", then the marked text will be saved to the user's
UUCP Mail directory instead.
@ENDNODE
@NODE JUMP "Will jump a Specified number of Lines DOWN into the document"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The JUMP COMMAND, issued by the "J" or "0" keys on the keyboard, allows
the user to jump ahead a specified number of lines.

   The default JUMP value will be half the number of rows in height the
AnsiRead window is currently set to.

   You can use the @{"SPACE BAR" link JUMPSET} to specify an alternate value for this "jump".
@ENDNODE
@NODE JUMPSET "Specify the number of rows to Jump Ahead"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The JUMP LINES command, issued by pressing the SPACE BAR on the keyboard,
allows you to specify the number of lines you wish to jump/skip ahead, when
using the @{"J / 0" link JUMP} command.
@ENDNODE
@NODE COUNT "Count or Highlight instances of text strings"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The COUNT command, issued by the "C" or "K" keys on the keyboard, allows
the user to find and count instances of a given text string. You will be
asked to enter a text string, whether or not you wish the counting to start
at the beginning of the text or at the current position, and whether or not
you wish the found instances to be highlighted for clarity.

   If the found instances are NOT highlighted, try toggling the MCI setting,
using the "Z" key.
@ENDNODE
@NODE IMPORT "Load an external text file into AnsiRead"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The IMPORT command, issued by the "I" key on the keyboard, allows you to
specify a path/filename to load into AnsiRead.

   The currently loaded text document will be overwritten by the contents of
the specified file.
@ENDNODE
@NODE TOGGLE "Toggle MCI Interpretation On / Off"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The TOGGLE MCI command, issued by the "Z" key on the keyboard, allows
the user to switch between MCI Interpretation, and "on-the-fly" stripping
of MCI codes.

   This is extremely useful when reading files that contain MCI commands
that can change the look of the screen, reposition the cursor, etc.

   Note, also, that the initial state of this command can be set by the
@{"SM variable" link SM}, or the @{"9th argument" link USING} specified in a {#0 } command.

NOTE:

   If, when using the @{"SEARCH" link SEARCH} or @{"COUNT" link COUNT} commands, you do NOT see found text
strings highlighted, try toggling the MCI. Chances are this will fix the
problem.
@ENDNODE
@NODE REDRAW "Lets you ReDraw the AnsiRead screen"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The REDRAW command, issued by the "R" key on the keyboard, lets you tell
AnsiRead to redraw it's display screen. This comes in handy when a text
document may contain extremely long lines, or embedded mci commands that
can influence how the text is shown on the screen.
@ENDNODE
@NODE QUIT "Lets you Quit AnsiRead"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The QUIT command, issued by the ESCAPE or "Q" keys on the keyboard, will
allow the user to quit out of AnsiRead. You'll first be ASKED if you really
want to quit, in case you decide not to for some reason.
@ENDNODE
@NODE HELP "Reviewing the Help Screen"
@TOC COMMANDS
   The HELP command, issued by the "?" or "/" keys on the keyboard, allow
you to switch back and forth between the current text document & AnsiRead's
Help Screen.

   Which screen appears first when starting AnsiRead can be set using the
@{"HF variable" link HF}, or by specifying the @{"11th argument" link USING} in the {#0 } command.
@ENDNODE
@NODE WHY "Why was AnsiRead originally Written?!?"
@TOC CONTENTS
   I actually started another program, before starting this one. I was in
the process of updating an old version of a Log Viewer when I decided to
rewrite the code from the ground up.

   AnsiRead was written ESPECIALLY for use with my "ViewLog, v5.00" file,
so if you haven't gotten ahold of this one yet, PLEASE DO! It's a file that
allows you to easily VIEW, TRIM, DELETE, and keep a HISTORY of ANY of the
predefined CNet logs, as well as ANY OTHER LOGS that may ALSO reside in the
SysData:Log/ directory. You can also specify some logs as being viewable by
the USERS on your bbs, so that THEY can get an idea as to the kinds of
things happening on the board too!

   Interested programmers can also use this file for an example of how to
implement the AnsiRead(er) into your own creations, as it also contains the
needed coding to BYPASS the AnsiRead program if it is NOT used. Check this
one out guys!
@ENDNODE
@NODE IDEAS "Some ideas on using AnsiRead on your bbs's"
@TOC CONTENTS
@NEXT MAIN
Here are some ideas for using AnsiRead on your bbs's:

    - Create an ARexx loader file to replace the CNet HELP System. The user
      could then use AnsiRead to view any/all help files on your system.

    - Replace your NEWS and/or GFILE section with calls to AnsiRead.

    - Include it as both a local and a remote text file viewer for use with
      the CD-Axe program. (Assumes CD-Axe, v2.03 by Heavy Metal/Ray Akey)

    - Include calls to it from within games for quick viewing and searching
      for information in the instructions files.

    - SysOps could replace the RF command with a call to AnsiRead.

    - Create SysOp-Only commands to read commonly used files, like the
      GetUserListing, where AnsiRead's search capability would come in
      really handy.

    - Replace CNet's Vote system with a program that would call AnsiRead in
      a small window at the top of the screen, where the vote topic would
      be displayed, while the lower portion of the screen could be used to
      show the vote choices.

   Keep in mind that these are ideas only. Feel free to experiment on your
own with AnsiRead, and don't hesitate to send me your ideas, problems, or
criticisms.

